The sulfide participation method distinguishes itself by higher removal efficiency and lesser dissolved solids increment than the hydroxide method. This method was reported to treat toxic heavy metal ions80. Lower sulfide results in a higher zinc concentration in the effluent, while higher sulfide leads to a malodor problem due to high residual sulfide. Also, it could produce hydrogen sulfide gas which is malodorous and toxic. For these reasons, the sulfide precipitation is recommended to be executed at a neutral pH81. The metal sulfide precipitations could follow Eq. (2) reaction,2Metaln++S2−⇔MetalnS↓\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
